\begin_layout Chapter*
Chapter One
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few weary-looking men were gathered around a standard-issue hololith table,
 badly scratched and flickering wildly, its blueish column of light shooting
 up straight to the ceiling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The grim expressions on most faces gave away their battle fatigue; their
 intermittent sleep pattern was etched in the hollow looks they exchanged
 silently.
 Echoes of grinding metal and mechanical stress reverberated all around
 them.
 An ear unaccustomed to spaceship life would have thought the walls were
 about to burst open and fill the small recreation hall with the cold, harsh
 void outside.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
None of the troops seemed to even register these sounds though.
 Their rock-solid attention was aimed at two pairs of hands dancing through
 the holographic projection, picking up tiny icons, shuffling through virtual
 inventories and linking up unit pieces.
 It was a peculiar sort of dance; sometimes brisk and unruly, but sometimes
 graceful.
 But it had a certain pace, a constant flow of motions; the two players
 of quadrachi never paused.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One pair of hands looked unmistakably feminine, while the other pair of
 hands looked scaled, leathery, and claw-like.
 A claw-like hand made a gesture and the holographic projection froze in
 place.
 Counters, graphs and icons flashed into life while the frozen quadrachi
 board rotated.
 A countdown timer appeared; the precious little pause wouldn't last very
 long by any measure.
 The woman's face was bathed in the blue holographic light as she leaned
 over the projected graphics.
 She seemed to smile thinly, looking straight into the eyes of her opponent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Want to surrender already, Han?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 she asked, twitching her lip into a mischievous grin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Han's oversized nostrils flared up, making a snorting sound.
 He wasn't smiling but instead he was scratching at the hololith table;
 his nervous routine had almost eaten through the carbosteel casing right
 down to the optronics inside.
 Han's breathing became short and heavy.
 The creaks and clangs of the ships reverberated around them, once more
 failing to catch anyone's attention.
 If it hadn't been for the timer ticking away closer to zero, one would
 perceive time had frozen still.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Han's attention was focused on a particular quadrant of the projection;
 he wore a dangerous-looking grin, revealing a quite lethal set of serrated
 teeth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Aren't you enjoying this Major Ciarandor? I thought this was a pleasurable
 experience for humans,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 he asked, his voice a rumbling sound, like a frothing river.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Only when playing against a Keplerian, Han.
 The blood-bet makes it so much more interesting,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Major Ciarandor replied.
 She sported an almost gleeful look and an imperceptibly wily smile.
 She seemed to be indeed enjoying herself immensely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

There's no meaning in loss without pain, Major.
 Wouldn't you agree?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 asked the Keplerian attachee, waving one arm in a surprisingly human fashion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It's what makes us learn from our mistakes, Han.
 Will you forfeit while the timer's ticking? Or shall we play?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the Major replied, pointing to the table with outstretched hands.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Have I ever let you down, Major?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Han in an uproar of wild laughter, fully revealing both sets of teeth
 in a jaw evolved for killing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the timer on the projection started flashing red, the awful sounds of
 the blaring proximity alert made Han's hand pause in mid-air right before
 he unpaused the game.
 As if a live grenade had been thrown among them, the men suddenly rushed
 outside the recreation room, grabbing their strewn-about equipment with
 a practiced, experienced haste.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Major and the Keplerian exchanged a knowing look; they'd continue their
 little match once the raid had been repelled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was the third one that cycle, and there was no sign that the Communion
 was going to leave them alone anytime soon.
 Ciarandor was last to get up and leave; mild-tempered and cool-headed,
 experience had taught her that there was time enough to pacefully walk
 to the command cupola.
 It was either that, or floating ice-cold dead in space amongst the ship's
 debris.
 There was no middle ground in space combat.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Keplerian was right at the doorway when he took notice and asked her
 with a slightly puzzled grin:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

No need for the commanding officer to rush, Major?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ciarandor shrugged as she put on her battle-dress jacket, saying: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

There is ample time, Ambassador Hanultheofodor.
 Can't wait to have your jaw around a Commie's neck?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Han's yellow-green eyes seemed to suddenly light up at the mere suggestion
 of physical violence.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm always ready for a fight.
 It only comes naturally to us,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 he said with a grin before turning his head towards the Major in an almost
 impossible angle before asking her: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

May I ask, why the formality all of a sudden?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Major put on her best dazzling smile and walked past the thickly built
 Keplerian.
 He looked impossibly imposing standing next to her deceptively lithe, fragile
 figure.
 As she reached for the access panel of the service elevator, she replied:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm supposed to remind you, your official capacity is that of an an observer.
 What if you get hurt in all the fighting and lose your tail?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 she said half-mockingly, bringing about a thunderous laughter from Han.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well then I'll have to grow another one, won't I?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 he casually said as he entered the elevator, barely being able to fit inside.
\end_layout

